    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1893-11-10T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1893-11-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="72" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d72">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Thompson</persName> to Mr.
                                <persName type="to">Gresham</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of
                                    the United States.</hi>
                            <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Petropolis</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1893-11-10">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 10, 1893</hi>
                        </date>.
                            (Received December 18.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 70.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to report that the U. S. S.
                            <hi rend="italic">Newark</hi> arrived at Rio de Janeiro October 19 and
                        on the 20th I had the pleasure of a call from Rear-Admiral Stanton at the U.
                        S. consulate, which I returned on Saturday the 21st and was received with
                        the usual formalities and great kindness by the admiral on board the <hi rend="italic">Newark.</hi>
                </p>
                <p>On the 22d I had occasion to visit the <hi rend="italic">Newarh</hi> again to
                        consult the <pb facs="0181" n="73" xml:id="pg_73"/> Admiral, and before my
                        departure Rear-Admiral de Mello, commander of the revolting squadron, came
                        on board. When the visitor was announced I signified my desire to leave, but
                        it was not convenient for me to do so at once, and a few minutes later I was
                        introduced by Admiral Stanton to the commander of the insurgent naval
                        forces. His visit was brief and seemed to be entirely of a social character,
                        as no allusion whatever was made to politics or the revolution.</p>
                <p>In this connection it may not be out of place for me to state in justice to
                        that gentleman that during his stay here and my official intercourse with
                        him I saw nothing whatever to indicate partiality on the part of Admiral
                        Stanton.</p>
                <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Thos. L. Thompson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
